‘Whoever tries a ssight in rivalry with Pindar, will surely fall like Icarus. That mighty poet pours forth his verse like mountain flood and is supreme in every field (1-24). He soars alost, a swan of Dirce, while Ι am but a Matine bee that gathers sweets with toil (25—32). But thou, Antonius, art a poet, and canst sing in fuller strain the tri- umphs of our supreme Caesar and hymn his glad return. Then Ι too will add my voice to swell the greeting (33—52). Thou shalt make large thanksgiving sacrifice of ten bulls and heffers, while Ι offer a young calf. as fits my humble station (53—60).'
